To synthesize the metal-organic framework, a mixture of Zn(NO3)2·6H2O (0.036 g, 0.12 mmol) and 1,3,5-benzenetricarboxylic acid (H3BTC) (0.025 g, 0.12 mmol) was dissolved in isobutanol (10 mL). The solution was transferred to a 30 mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave, which was tightly sealed and heated at 173.278 °C for 223.01 hours. After gradually cooling to room temperature, yellowish needle-shaped crystals of the framework were obtained with a yield of 61% based on Zn. Elemental analysis calculated for C18H18O12Zn2: C, 39.62, H, 3.33. Found: C, 39.45, H, 3.35. IR spectra (KBr, cm−1) displayed the following peaks: 3430(s, br), 1660(m), 1595(s), 1450(m), 1380(s), 1267(m), 1122(w), 883(m), 750(s). Single-crystal X-ray analysis revealed that the framework crystallizes in the tetragonal I4/mmm space group. The structure comprises Zn2(COO)4 paddle-wheel units interconnected by BTC ligands, forming a three-dimensional porous network. The resulting

A solution of Ni(NO3)2·6H2O (34.5 mg, 0.12 mmol) and 1,3,5-benzenetricarboxylic acid (21.0 mg, 0.1 mmol) was prepared in a solvent mixture of isobutanol (10 mL) and glycol (0.5 mL). The mixture was stirred for 30 minutes at ambient temperature until homogeneous. Subsequently, the mixture was transferred into a 50 mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave and subjected to static heating at 253.26 °C for 487.45 hours. After the reaction period, the system was allowed to cool slowly to room temperature at a rate of 2 °C per hour, resulting in the formation of pale green hexagonal crystals of the Ni-MOF, which were isolated by filtration and washed with isobutanol. Yield: ~72% based on Ni. The crystalline product was further characterized via elemental analysis, yielding results consistent with theoretical calculations: Found – C, 45.31, H, 4.23, N, 2.17%. IR (KBr pellet, cm−1): 3421(br, s), 2941(m), 1623(s), 1436(vs), 1357(s), 1208(m), 1139(w), 789(s), 662(w), 534(vs).

The mixture was transferred to a 25 mL Teflon-lined stainless-steel autoclave and heated at 169 °C for 352.27 minutes. A mixture of Cu(NO3)2·3H2O (0.060 g, 0.25 mmol) and H3btc (0.042 g, 0.20 mmol) was dissolved in methanol (10 mL) in a 30 mL teflon-lined autoclave. The vessel was sealed and heated in an oven to 175.1 °C for 129.82 hours, after which it was allowed to cool to room temperature naturally. Blue cubic crystals suitable for X-ray diffraction were isolated by filtration with a yield of 72% based on Cu(NO3)2·3H2O. The crystalline compound was characterized by elemental analysis, revealing a composition consistent with Cu3(btc)2·(CH3OH)6. Anal. Calcd for C18H24Cu3O12: C, 36.45, H, 4.08, Found: C, 36.51, H, 4.05. The phase purity was confirmed by powder XRD, matching the simulated pattern (see Figure S3, Supporting Information). IR (KBr pellet, cm−1): 3440(m), 1610(s), 1440(s), 1383(s), 1105(m), 963(w), 840(m), 720(w), 650(w).

ZrCl4 (0.120 g, 0.515 mmol) and terephthalic acid (0.086 g, 0.519 mmol) were combined in a 30 mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave with benzene (10 mL) as the solvent and Et3N (0.1 mL) as an additive to promote deprotonation. The metal-organic framework, designated as MOF-2, was synthesized under solvothermal conditions. In a typical synthesis, 0.300 g (0.984 mmol) of copper(II) nitrate trihydrate was dissolved in 10 mL of dimethylacetamide (DMA). To this solution, 0.150 g (0.492 mmol) of 1,4-benzenedicarboxylic acid was added. Additionally, 0.200 mL of triethylamine (N(Et)3) was introduced to facilitate the deprotonation of the ligand. The resulting mixture was transferred into a 25 mL Teflon-lined autoclave, which was then sealed and heated at 307.7 K for 500.6 minutes. Upon completion, the reaction was allowed to cool to ambient temperature, yielding pale blue crystalline solids. These were collected by filtration, washed with fresh DMA, and dried under ambient conditions. The MOF-2 was obtained with an 82% yield based on copper. Elemental analysis results showed C, 49.82%, H, 5.17%, N, 2.31%. Experimental values found were C, 49.63%, H, 5.09%, N, 2.25%. FTIR (KBr, cm−1): 3430 (m), 1622 (s), 1578 (m), 1440 (s),

Synthesis. The metal-organic framework [MOF-123] was synthesized through solvothermal methods by combining metal precursors and organic linkers. In a 50 mL Schlenk flask, 0.500 g (1.0 mmol) of cobalt nitrate hexahydrate and 0.200 g (1.5 mmol) of terephthalic acid were dissolved in 20 mL of acetonitrile to form a homogeneous solution. Subsequently, 0.050 mL (0.3 mmol) of HBF4 was added dropwise with continuous stirring to stabilize the intermediate species and enhance crystallinity. The mixture was then transferred to a Teflon-lined autoclave, sealed, and heated to 434.2 K for 37.09 hours under autogenous pressure. Upon completion, the autoclave was allowed to cool down to room temperature naturally. Pale pink crystals of MOF-123 were isolated by filtration, washed with additional acetonitrile, and dried under vacuum. The crystalline product was obtained in a yield of 75%, confirmed to be phase-pure by powder X-ray diffraction analysis. Elemental analysis of the product indicated satisfactory agreement with the calculated values, confirming the stoichiometry and integrity of the framework. The crystals exhibited robust structural features with high thermal stability as indicated by thermogravimetric analysis.

A solution of Cu(NO3)2·3H2O (0.242 g, 1 mmol), H2bdc (0.166 g, 1 mmol), and pyrazine (0.080 g, 1 mmol) was prepared in dimethyl sulfoxide (10 mL). The resulting mixture was transferred into a 20 mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave. The vessel was sealed and maintained under autogenous pressure at a temperature of 430.6 K for 38.305 minutes. Upon completion, the system was gradually cooled to room temperature, yielding pale green rod-like crystals. The crystals were isolated by filtration, washed with DMSO carefully, and air-dried. The yield of the crystalline product was approximately 85%, calculated based on the initial copper content. To synthesize the metal-organic framework, a mixture of the ligand H2BDC (benzene-1,4-dicarboxylic acid, 50 mg, 0.30 mmol) and Zn(NO3)2·6H2O (89 mg, 0.30 mmol) was combined in dimethylacetamide (10 mL) within a 20 mL glass vial. An additive, 1,3-dimethylurea (25 mg, 0.25 mmol), was introduced to the solution to facilitate crystal growth. The vial was sealed tightly and subjected to controlled heating at 36.29 °C for 33.393 hours. Afterward, upon returning to ambient temperature slowly over several hours, the crystalline product was isolated via filtration and rinsed with methanol to remove residual solvent. The resulting colorless crystals were identified as the desired MOF with framework formula [Zn4O(BDC)3]·(DMF) and were isolated in 68% yield. X-ray diffraction analysis confirmed the structural integrity and phase purity. IR (KBr, cm−1): 1605, 1508, 1401, 1310, 1256, 1103, 1020, 804, 742, 670, 612. Anal. for C48H30N2O16Zn4: Calcd: C 50.70%, H 2.66%, N

After the reaction time elapsed, the autoclave was cooled naturally to room temperature. The resulting green crystalline MOF was collected by filtration, washed thoroughly with ethanol to remove any residual reactants, and air-dried. The purity and crystalline structure of the MOF were confirmed by powder X-ray diffraction analysis, which matched well with the theoretical pattern based on single-crystal data.

The resulting green crystalline MOF was collected by filtration, washed thoroughly with ethanol to remove any residual reactants, and air-dried. A mixture containing Zn(NO3)2·6H2O (0.30 mmol, 89 mg) and terephthalic acid (0.20 mmol, 33 mg) was dissolved in 5 mL of CH3CH2OH, to which AcOH (0.2 mL) was subsequently added. The resulting solution was transferred to a 10 mL microwave reactor, which was then sealed and heated at 85 °C for 6.39 minutes under constant microwave irradiation. Once the heating period was complete, the mixture was allowed to cool naturally to room temperature. The product formed as white rod-like crystals were isolated by filtration, washed thoroughly with ethanol (3 mL, 3 times), and dried under vacuum for 30 minutes (Yield: 58%, 0.018 g considering terephthalic acid). The composition and purity of the resulting Zn-MOF were confirmed by elemental analysis: found C = 43.12%, H = 3.28%, Zn = 14.63%, calculated C = 43.45%, H = 3.40%, Zn = 14.89%. Compound 2 was synthesized via a solvothermal method: a mixture of Cu(NO3)2·3H2O (0.728 g, 3.00 mmol) and terephthalic acid (0.332 g, 2.00 mmol) was dissolved in 40 mL of ethanol (EtOH). The solution was thoroughly stirred at room temperature for 1 hour and then sealed in a 100 mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave. The autoclave was placed in an oven and maintained at 423.035 K for 256.238 hours. Upon cooling to room temperature, blue crystalline MOF structures were obtained. The crystals were washed thoroughly with ethanol, filtered, and air-dried, yielding 52.7% based on copper. Elemental analysis calculated for the framework: C, 42.56, H, 2.85, N, 1.10. Found: C, 42.64, H, 2.90, N, 1.12. Characteristic IR bands were observed at 1612, 1504, and 1387 cm−1, indicative of the coordination environment. Thermogravimetric analysis revealed a structural stability with decomposition commencing at 300 °C.

The vanadium-based metal-organic framework, [VF6(bpy)], was synthesized via solvothermal methods starting from vanadium(V) oxide. In a typical synthesis, 0.095 g of V2O5 was dissolved in 10 mL of dimethylformamide (DMF) with continuous stirring to ensure complete dissolution. To this solution, 0.210 g of 4,4'-bipyridine was added and the reaction mixture was subjected to further stirring at room temperature for 45 minutes, achieving a molar ratio of 1.0 V2O5: 3.0 bpy: 500 DMF. The homogeneous mixture was then sealed in a 25-mL Teflon-lined autoclave and heated at 221.85 °C for approximately 124.41 minutes. Upon cooling to room temperature, the resulting crystalline product, characterized by its hexagonal shapes, was isolated through vacuum filtration and rinsed sparingly with fresh DMF to remove any unreacted starting materials. The desired framework was obtained with a yield of ~70% based on vanadium input. The synthesis resulted in structurally robust crystals suitable for further characterization and potential application explorations in gas adsorption studies.

To synthesize the novel metal-organic framework (MOF) compound, 0.250 g of cobalt(II) nitrate hexahydrate (Co(NO3)2·6H2O) was combined with 0.200 g of 1,4-benzenedicarboxylic acid (H2BDC) in 10 mL of diethylformamide. To this mixture, 0.50 mL of acetic acid (CH3COOH) was added to assist in modulating the crystallization process. The resulting solution was homogenized for 20 minutes under ambient conditions and then transferred to a 25 mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave. The sealed autoclave was heated to 97 °C and maintained at this temperature for 161.205 hours. Upon completion of the reaction, the system was allowed to cool naturally to room temperature. The resulting pink prism-shaped crystals were isolated by filtration, washed with diethyl ether, and dried under vacuum. The yield of the product was approximately 67% based on cobalt(II) nitrate. The integrity of the framework was confirmed by powder X-ray diffraction, showing characteristic peaks at 2θ = 8.5°, 10.2°, and 18.9°. All chemicals used were of analytical grade and used without further purification. A new metal-organic framework (MOF) was synthesized from a mixture of zinc nitrate hexahydrate (Zn(NO3)2·6H2O), terephthalic acid, and 1,4-diazabicyclo[2.2.2]octane (DABCO) in the presence of dimethylformamide (DMF) as a solvent. Approximately 0.5 g of Zn(NO3)2·6H2O and 0.25 g of terephthalic acid were dissolved in 15 mL DMF, followed by the addition of 0.1 g DABCO and a catalytic amount of hexafluoropropene. The mixture was stirred vigorously at room temperature until a homogeneous solution was achieved. Subsequently, the solution was transferred to a 50 mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave, which was filled to 60% of its total volume capacity. The vessel was then sealed and heated to 125 °C for 128.74 minutes under autogenous pressure. After the heating period, the autoclave was allowed to cool to room temperature. Colorless, needle-shaped crystals of the MOF were collected via filtration, washed with DMF, and dried under vacuum. The yield of the product was approximately 45% based on the initial zinc content. The resulting mixture was stirred for 15 minutes until a homogenous solution was obtained. The pH was adjusted to approximately 4.5 by dropwise addition of 0.1 M HNO3. The mixture was then transferred into a Teflon-lined reactor and heated at 317.127 K for 161.62 minutes under static conditions. After gradual cooling to room temperature, the precipitated yellow cubic crystals were filtered off and washed with cold N,N-dimethylacetamide and ethanol to remove any unreacted starting materials. A novel MOF, designated as MOF-XYZ, was synthesized by combining 0.50 g (1.5 mmol) cobalt(II) nitrate hexahydrate and 0.25 g (1.0 mmol) benzene-1,3,5-tricarboxylic acid (H3BTC) in 10 mL of ethanol as a solvent. To this solution, 1 mL of triethylamine (N(Et)3) was added to facilitate deprotonation of the organic ligand. The reaction mixture was transferred to a 40 mL glass vial, sealed, and heated in an oil bath at a controlled temperature of 62.411 °C for 147 minutes. After the specified heating period, slow cooling to room temperature proceeded over a span of 6 hours. Upon completion, blue crystalline materials of MOF-XYZ were obtained, which were collected by filtration, washed with ethanol, and dried under vacuum for 24 hours. The yield was 72%, based on cobalt(II) nitrate hexahydrate. Characterization by PXRD confirmed the crystalline structure, with key peaks observed at 2θ = 8.1°, 12.3°, and 25.4°. The IR spectrum revealed characteristic bands at 3410 (m), 1610 (s), 1435 (m), and 1108 (s) cm−1, as shown in Figure S1 of the supplementary information

In a 50 mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave, a homogenized mixture comprising 0.125 g of Zn(NO3)2·6H2O (0.42 mmol), 0.074 g of 1,4-benzenedicarboxylic acid (0.44 mmol), and 15 mL of dimethyl sulfoxide (68-12-2) was prepared. The autoclave was firmly sealed and subjected to a thermal treatment at 365.19 K for 379.257 hours. Upon completion of the reaction, the system was allowed to cool gradually to room temperature. The resulting solid, consisting of transparent colorless crystals of the Zn-based MOF, was isolated through filtration and subsequently washed with ethanol. For a typical synthesis, copper(II) nitrate trihydrate (242 mg, 1.00 mmol), benzene-1,4-dicarboxylic acid (HO2C-C6H4-CO2H, 166 mg, 1.00 mmol), and 2-methylimidazole (82 mg, 1.00 mmol) were dissolved in methanol (20 mL) in a 50 mL round-bottom flask. The solution was stirred vigorously at room temperature for 15 minutes to ensure complete dissolution of the reactants. The mixture was transferred to a 50 mL Teflon-lined stainless-steel autoclave and heated in an oven at 168.01 °C for 191 minutes. Upon completion of the reaction time, the autoclave was allowed to cool to room temperature naturally. The resultant blue crystalline product was subjected to repeated washing with fresh methanol (25 mL) for three cycles to remove any unreacted ligands or metal salts. The isolated product was dried under vacuum at 100 °C for 6 hours, resulting in pure copper-based MOF labeled Cu-BDC-MeIm, with a yield of 0.358 g corresponding to a 78% yield based on copper nitrate trihydrate starting material. Compound [Fe3(BTC)2(H2O)12] was synthesized via a hydrothermal reaction using FeCl3·6H2O (0.162 g, 0.6 mmol) and trimesic acid (BTC) (0.063 g, 0.3 mmol) in deionized water (15 mL) with the addition of 1 mL of concentrated HBF4. The mixture was transferred into a 25 mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave, sealed, and heated to 314 K for 193.4 minutes. The reaction was then allowed to cool to room temperature naturally. Pale yellow cubic crystals were isolated by filtration and thoroughly washed with distilled water. Yield: 72 %. Elemental analysis calculated for [Fe3(BTC)2(H2O)12] (C18H12Fe3O24): C, 26.14, H, 1.46, found: C, 26.11, H, 1.48. IR (KBr): ν(cm–1) = 3412 (s), 2925 (w), 1675 (m), 1543 (s), 1384 (vs), 1245 (m), 778 (m) (see Figure S3, Supporting Information). The compound's structure was confirmed by single-crystal X-ray diffraction and further supported by thermogravimetric analysis (TGA).

A novel metal-organic framework (MOF-66) was synthesized by combining Cu(NO3)2·3H2O (0.242 g, 1 mmol), terephthalic acid (0.166 g, 1 mmol), and 2,2'-bipyridine (0.156 g, 1 mmol) in dimethyl acetamide (50 mL). Sulfuric acid (0.1 mL) was added as a modulator to the reaction mixture. The sealed vial was subjected to heating at 331.350 K for 447.291 minutes. After cooling to room temperature, the resulting blue crystalline solid was collected by filtration and washed thoroughly with dimethyl acetamide. The material was then dried under vacuum at ambient temperature, affording MOF-66 with a yield of 75%. Powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) confirmed phase purity and crystallinity, while SEM analysis revealed the formation of closely packed hexagonal crystals with sizes ranging between 50−150 μm (Figure 3). IR spectra displayed characteristic peaks at 3421s, 2942m, 1718s, 1466w, and 1208m cm−1, confirming the successful incorporation of the organic linkers into the framework.

Synthesis of Co-MOF: Co(NO3)2·6H2O (0.291 g, 1 mmol) and 1,4-benzenedicarboxylic acid (0.083 g, 0.5 mmol) were dissolved in 12 mL of dimethyl formamide. Subsequently, 0.1 g of sodium acetate was added to the solution to serve as a modulating agent. The resulting mixture was heated to 91.4 °C and maintained at this temperature for 266.22 minutes. Upon cooling to room temperature, a crop of purple block-shaped crystals was collected by filtration and washed with DMF to ensure purity. The yield of the product was 0.205 g, equating to 78% based on the molar ratio of 1,4-benzenedicarboxylic acid. Infrared spectroscopy (IR, KBr, cm−1) indicated prominent peaks at 3432(m), 2925(m), 1698(s), 1579(s), 1453(m), 1388(s), 1265(m), 1146(m), 1012(w), 808(m), 755(m), and 618(w). Elemental analysis calculated for CoC18H18O10: C 45.42, H 3.81, found: C 45.10, H 3.92, highlighting the consistency with the expected framework composition.

To synthesize the desired metal-organic framework under the specified conditions, a measured amount of Cu(NO3)2·3H2O (0.5 mmol) and terephthalic acid (0.25 mmol) were initially dissolved in ethanol (10 mL). To this solution, KOH (0.1 g, 0.25 mmol) was carefully added while stirring. The resulting mixture was transferred to a 50 mL Teflon-lined autoclave. The assembly was sealed and subjected to a hydrothermal process at 170.950 °C for 207.817 hours. After the allotted time, the autoclave was allowed to slowly cool to ambient temperature at a rate of approximately 0.1 °C·min–1. The crystallized product, consisting of light blue needle-shaped crystals, was separated by filtration, thoroughly washed with ethanol, and subsequently air-dried. The uniformity and phase purity of the synthesized MOF were verified by matching the powder X-ray diffraction patterns with the simulated ones (Supplementary Fig. S5). Additional characterization through FTIR spectroscopy revealed distinct peaks at 3410(m), 1635(s), 1382(s), 1103(m), and 780(w) cm–1, confirming the successful formation of the framework.

All chemical reagents employed were of high purity and analytical grade. The metal-organic framework was synthesized by combining zinc nitrate hexahydrate (Zn(NO3)2·6H2O) and 1,4-benzenedicarboxylic acid (BDC) in the presence of the solvent methanol and the additive hexafluoropropene. Typically, 0.300 g Zn(NO3)2·6H2O (1.01 mmol) and 0.160 g BDC (0.63 mmol) were dissolved in 15 ml methanol with vigorous stirring. Subsequently, 2 ml of hexafluoropropene was added dropwise to the reaction mixture under continuous stirring at ambient temperature. The resultant solution was transferred to a 25 ml Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave, occupying approximately 65% of its volume capacity, ensuring a well-sealed environment. The autoclave was then heated at 172.820 °C for 307.14 minutes under autogeneous pressure. Upon completion of the reaction time, the autoclave was cooled slowly to room temperature. The formed colorless cube-like crystals were collected by filtration, thoroughly washed with methanol, and air-dried. The final product was obtained in a yield of 70% based on BDC. Elemental analysis was consistent with the calculated composition of [Zn(BDC)(H2O)·(C3F6H2)n

In a 25 mL glass vial, a mixture of Zn(NO3)2·6H2O (29.7 mg, 0.1 mmol) and 1,3,5-benzenetricarboxylic acid (H3BTC, 21.0 mg, 0.1 mmol) was dissolved in 10 mL of diethylformamide (DEF). Subsequently, 0.4 mL of concentrated HNO3 was added as an additive. The vial was sealed and the reaction mixture was placed in a water bath at 308 K for 225.52 minutes to allow for crystallization. Upon cooling to ambient temperature, the vial was opened, yielding white crystalline solids. The precipitate was collected by vacuum filtration and washed thrice with DEF and then methanol to enhance purity. The crystals were dried under reduced pressure, affording a yield of 48% based on the initial metal salt. Elemental analysis calculated for C18H12N3O12Zn: C, 40.32, H, 2.26, N, 7.83%.
